This is a clip that connects your Wiimote to your Classic Controller. The bottom of the clip connects to the Wiimote; the top half clips into those as-of-yet unused holes at the bottom of the Classic Controller (using that mystery middle shoulder button). The clip could be good for (a) getting the wiimote out of the way and (b) for any games that may want to have a mix between dual-analog controls and motion-sensitive controls. Featured a few years back on websites such as:
http://kotaku.com/gaming/wii-remote/wii-remote--classic-controller-in-unholy-union-237743.php
http://www.joystiq.com/2007/02/19/diy-nintendo-wii-classic-controller-clip-holds-your-wiimote-so/
http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2007/02/diy_nintendo_wii_classic.html

Due to the overhangs, you'll need a printer that can handle support material.
The first clip was made on a SLA250. I've since made clips on a various FDM machines and even on an old Thermojet.  
The clip can fail at the Classic Controller interface; the undercut wall is fairly thin. So far, my SLA-made clips have survived fairly well (the others, not so much).

description.text:
This is a 2/3-pieces tool mount for anyone who wanna try with 2.2kW Chinese spindle (DIA 80mm). The mount works with F-ToolMount MPCNC 525 (25mm OD) as in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:790533/#files
The spindle itself is probably too heavy(ca.4.5kg) for the standard MPCNC design if it comes to rigidity and axis movement capability.. Additional reinforcements, frame size decrease, reducing motor speed or change to bigger torque motor(especially for Z) would help. You can find some MPCNC modifications/heavy duty versions on thingiverse..
I tried to keep the spindle close to Z axis to keep it more rigid. As result there is a collision with two bolt heads so they need to be blended slightly(see photos for details)..
The bottom part have a flange to prevent spindle to slide down. I used two upper parts for better support. You will need 1x M5x25mm and 2x M4x20mm for each mount part.

23/04/17 Update:
As requested I added mount version for 1.5kW spindle with 65mm DIA. Bottom part inner flange has 45mm DIA. I don't have such spindle so let me know how it works...

description.text:
Hello,

I created a frame which I could print on a 200x200mm printer bed.
This frame has a mount for a 30x30mm FC and a 30x30mm PDB.
Underneath you can assemble a receiver and FPV transmitter perfectly. On top there is enough space for the battery.
A mounting place for a cam is there as well.
The ESCs are hidden under the arms and like this, a pretty nice build emerges.
For the feet I chose a pretty easy solution and you need some clue to fixate them. I think about another solution. I will add a motor protection later on.

For the assembly you need somer spacers. I bought this amazon set: https://www.amazon.de/INIBUD-Abstandhalter-Schrauben-Muttern-Schwarz/dp/B01CG9KATS/ref=sr_1_1?s=diy&ie=UTF8&qid=1481625564&sr=1-1&keywords=INIBUD+180+Stk+M3+Nylon+Hex+Abstandhalter+Schrauben+Muttern+Kit+Schwarz+Drohn

//EDIT:
I had a first flight (and a second) and I am pretty new to FPV, so I had a rather rough landing (you could say crash) and instantly found some weak points of the construction. I will rework it and bring a new version with 4 seperate arms to assemble, and reinforced arms etc.
The feet are rather bad positioned... because of the lever between the weight and the contact point to the ground. I will rework this as well.

Have a good print
Carsten

description.text:
SMART SPOOL with Built-in Bearings
When assembled, these parts make a standard size 1KG Filament spool 165mm (w) x 84mm (h) with a special feature: the spool has a built-in bearing mechanism that helps it spin smoothly when installed inside a printer like the Tiko!

All parts are 125mm x 84mm in size or smaller, allowing the parts to be printed on a Tiko printer, which has an internal bay for filament spools of this size.

The (optional) bearing mechanism and spindle can be inserted into the lower portion of the hub, allowing the spool to spin freely when mounted inside a 3D printer like the Tiko. An optional extender increases the size of the spool to 84mm high -- the exact height of a standard 165mm 1KG spool.

To assemble:
1) Locate the upper hub marked with LL(eft) and R(ight), T(op) and B(ottom), then glue the corresponding rims in place using Super Glue, Krazy Glue or similar.
2) The lower hub and rims are labeled with L and T only; glue these rims to the corresponding sections of the lower hub.

It is not necessary to glue the screw-together parts. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:352657 for information on how to wind filament onto this spool.

2016-12-21 update: I've posted the uncut top and bottom spool parts for those with access to printers with a print bed size of at least 165mm x 165mm. Those with Tiko printers do not need the "uncut" files.

2016-12-23 update: At this time, the file Smart_Spool-bearing.stl is proving impossible to print on Tiko. Until Tiko provides a working method of adding support, or further improves its raft, I have provided a workaround file SS_Bearing_w_Helper_Ring.stl that includes a .4mm "artificial raft" ring that should help to hold the bearings in place while they are printed on a Tiko. Users of other printers do not need to use this file. (And Tiko should not require it either!) If you use this file, you will have to manually remove the ring of support material from below the bearing cylinders in order for them to spin as intended.

If Tiko owners find other models that don't stay put (Rocketz by muzz64 comes to mind) on the raft, this technique can be used on virtually any model by adding one or more "Helper Disks" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:346319) below the parts you want to hold in place in order to print them on a Tiko. Good luck!

comments.text:
Yes, I have these parts. However, I recommend that you spend a moment to learn how easy it is to merge parts back into one piece. I used the Merge command in Microsoft's free 3D Builder to do this for you in about a minute. There are many other tools that could do this, too. But 3D Builder is free and easy to use. Learning techniques like this is worthwhile. Here's how I did it:
1) Load 3D Builder, Load Object > Smart_Spool-lower-hub.stl > Import model
2) Insert > + Add > Load Object > Smart_Spool-lower-LR.stl > Import model
3) Ungroup. Click the left side part to deselect it; drag the other side into position, touching the hub.
4) Repeat for other parts. (Click Repair if any files say they need to be repaired when you add them.)
5) When done, Select all, Edit > Merge. Save as [filename].stl. (I recommend saving the upper assembly and lower assembly as separate STLs.)
6) Done! Load these STLs one at a time into your favorite slicer and prep for printing as usual.

description.text:
Well, now that I have found out about the scad "surface" primitive, the sky is the limit.

This project is intended to be a prop for Paizo's "Wrath of the Righteous" campaign. In this campaign one of the main antagonists is the demon lord Bephomet, Lord of the Ivory Labyrinth.

This will be a complicated little project, but eminently do-able now that I can 3d-print. The baphomet sign will be printed in clear plastic (mirrored so that it's all double sided) and supported between a pair of infinity mirrors. At each point of the star I will mount an Adafruit Neopixel, which will be driven by an arduino - I'll make the colour sort of slowly cycling red/orange.

Additionally, I'd like to have a couple of really small LEDs at the eyes, and I'd like to etch a labryinth motif into the polycarbonate infinity mirrors, which I will illuminate in white (maybe a little blue) for colour contrast.

The whole thing will be built - say - four inches across. 20ft at D&D scale. We use Dwarven Forge tiles, so the base should be compatible. I might have it "up" a bit so as to have more room in the base for batteries and the arduino.

For bonus points, I might be able to make it controllable via bluetooth: colour, speed, flash the eyes sinisterly.

When it's done and we have finally defeated Baphomet and Deskari and saved Golarion from the hordes of the Abyss - or then again, perhaps not - I'll sell the thing on Etsy.

17-Dec

Very happy with the holder. Holds the neopixels against the sprues at the end of the Baphomet nice and snug. Printed off with no support, so support for the thin part of the ring is built into the design - it printed without fuss and broke away perfectly.

19-Dec

Redid the Baphomet symbol completly. I found a balck-and-white image on the web with just the Paizo-style logo - wit the weird flamy headstalk. Quite a bit of faffing about with several editing programs: gimp, meshmixer, meshlab. In gimp, I made the black surround a mask and blurred the central white area with the surrounding black. This gave be a contoured heightmap with a crisp edge.

The forehed and nose are a flat area, so I tried contouring them with meshmixer. But every time, as soon as I touched the STL, OpenScad couldn't read it anymore. Something to so with triangles. In the end, I just used the surface() primitive and got a result, flat forehead and all.

Printed with Slic3r. Rectangular fill, coincentric top layer, no bottom layer. Clear PLA. If you go with coincentric fill, which you thing would be good, what happens is that the ring gets all thready and pulls apart.

I think I shall have to extend the sprues, to a) get the holder away from the logo and b) make room for the horns. Quite a lot of light leaking, which doesn't look cool. Perhaps if I extend the sprues and wrap some black electrical tape around them. Some sort of cap for the gap in the open side of the sprue holder bit might be the go, too.

But it's getting to a point where the holder and the central moulding is good enough. I shall have to start thinking about hijacking some of the OpenForge pieces to make the body of the portal. The peice should have a maze there, as Baphomet in Pathfinder is "lord of the ivory labryinth".

27-Dec

I have built a pair of modules to allow the building of openforge-sized walls and floors, which can of course be combined into corners and whatnot.

Most notably, these modules allow you to pass in wall and floor textures as submodules. I have not had much luck putting the maze logo on the polycarbonate - printing kinda works, but is very fiddly. What I need is a CNC machine, which I don't have.

So I will settle for printing a maze logo into the frame and its surrounding tiles. The logo will be hideously complicated, so I'll develop it using just a shape for the logo, then put in the labyrinth .stl later.

01-Jan

Well, problems, problems. What I want is to do a union of a background of bones (2mm) and a foreground of a labyrinth (3.7mm). But these things just won't union properly. The stls are too complicated or something.

I have abandoned using 'surface' on the labyrinth logo, instead just writing some scad to build it. I might try 'surface'-ing the bones at much lower res.

05-Feb

Well, well, well! Turns out that Baphomet's "Ivory Labyrinth" is ivory because it's made out of bone!

I have added a slight modification to the openforge module - a chamfer from the "lower floor" texture to the "upper floor" texture. Improves it a great deal, I think, although it does add more complexity.

I may have to rethink things a bit - the module will not behave well when you attempt to make a textured corner. I have a "floor inset", but I may need a "wall inset".

And my Lord don't these things take a while to render!

A replica of the SE-14R Blastech blaster used by the Storm Troopers and the side arm for the Death Troopers. I tried to model this as accurately as I could. It is still a work in progress but I wanted to get it out there in case anyone wanted to print it for the Rogue One premiere parties and festivities.

  • Revised to break the gun into parts for easier editing and added in a few details including a better handle.
  • Revised the model so that the barrel ends can screw on
  • Revised the model so that a push button switch can be put inside the handle just behind the trigger.
  • Revised the handle so that it is hollow to handle some electronics and a hole up to the barrel
  • Revised the barrel and slid so that the slide can be racked back partially so simulate cocking the blaster

Its free to use but if you make one and use it in your costume, please leave me a tip for pizza money so I can at least justify some of my time to my wife. Thanks.

For the last year I have been out of work as I worked to save my son from cancer. During the last year he has been in and out of the hospital and I have seen the power of the 501st when it visits a children's hospital. It was this experience which motivates me. I hope you find my work worth while.

title: Solder Fume Extrator - Backstop with Spacer Ring

description.text:
Thanks to sneakypoo for his awesome Solder Fume Extractor design!

sneakypoo constructed the head for three filter layers á 1cm. That seemed like an overkill and I only wanted to use two filters. But as you can see in a lot of makes of this fume extractor: If you use less than three filters they do not align perfectly and look wavy or bumpy when squeezed into the head.

So I came up with this very simple redesign of the optional backstop. It now hosts a 1cm high spacer ring. This way, two filters stack on top of each other and neatly align with the rest of the head. No waves, no bumps. :-)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

22%

Notes:

You need supports to print the backstop spacer correctly. I used a rather close-meshed grid support.

My print needed some rework at the ends of the backstop inserts. There was too much friction and I couldn't slide them easily into the head. Light sanding helped. But beware! The spacer ring and the ends of the backstop are only connected in a single, small spot. Depending on your amount of infill they may brake (I'm speaking from experience;-). Nothing that a drop of super glue can't solve.

description.text:
My old Fiat 850 originally had a "spare tire powered" windscreen washer, i.e., a water bottle pressurized by the air from the spare tire, and a simple button letting the water pass to the washers. After more than 40 years this system is no more, and instead there is a "conventional" water bag and an electrically driven pump.
The conversion wasn't too bad, but the button and the way it was being held in place were in need of some 3D magic.
So I designed a bracket to fit the electrical switch (a heavy dutyy, general purpose button switch with a 22mm(?) thread (26 tpi?)) and a button with the winscreen washer symbol.
The photo shows the finished button (left), the remains of the original bracket (center), and the remains of the original rubber button (right)

BQ Prusa

Notes:

I printed the button at 100%, face down.

The button was sanded and sort of polished with steel wool and a scrubbing pad.
I actually printed the button face down, and because I forgot to remove the support option, had to rework the symbol, removing excess material with a thin piano wire.
I used correction fluid to fill the symbol, removing the excess by sanding and scraping.
Finished it all with a clear wax.

title: Thermography Camera 30 degree tilt weather cover

description.text:
This is a lens attachment to protect thermal cameras against environmental effects, e.g. rain or dust. The frontal surface is tilted by 30 degree, so that the camera does not get thermal image reflection from its own sensor. The frontal surface should be covered by stretch foil (Celophan). There are two variations: the larger one 74mm, should fit onto the Infratec VARIOCAM HD standard lens, while the smaller version should fit on a Infratec Head camera. One can doublecheck, the diameter is printed in the the original protection cover inside.
I propose to print with no infill, to have better thermal insulation, since otherwise the infill pattern might cause miniscule reflection patterns. I have not printed them yet, nor tried them yet.
